<HR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uperplexcerebrum.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Perplex Cerebrum</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://images.honesty.com/imagedata/h/920/44/29204482.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(9/21/01 12:03:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumcleric.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=210.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://images.honesty.com/imagedata/h/920/44/29204481.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: lv 55</span><hr size=1> I'll chip in my $0.02, for what its worth.<br>
<br>
 Fortitude -- very much a useless spell. The story goes that Fortitude was designed before the Heroic Bond messup, and it was supposed to be an upgrade to the HP spell that they originally had in store for clerics at level 51, which was supposed to be called Heroic Resolve if I remember correctly. Heroic Bond was initially supposed to be a high 50s spell, and an upgrade to Heroic Resolve. So the history was meant to be... BUT, they put HB in at wrong level, way before we were actually supposed to get it, which in effect created an obsolete spell, Fortitude. Once it was in, they didn't change it for whatever reasons, and from what I hear Verant considers HB a &quot;gift&quot; to cleric community. <br>
<br>
<br>
Stun Command -- I personally haven't had a lot of resist problems and I really like this spell. Cool thing about it is that it works differently from chanter stuns because the AE goes out from the target, not the caster, which creates some interesting possibilities. <br>
<br>
 Some things to try out with this spell which you might find entertaining, if not useful.<br>
<br>
a) 4-5 mobs are incoming, in Sebilis or Velks for example. You cast Stun Command on one of the approaching mobs... you hear the Swoosh sound and then... silence. The action is frozen in time. For one, it gives your chanter more time to react and also, any mob that resists and keeps coming towards you is either higher level or has more MR so it would be good to kill it first anyway. Same goes when you suddenly get 3 adds while 3 mobs are already mezzed in camp. Why I love this spell is because it gives you a way to help out in handling the situation, as well as provides a bit of variety to our usual jobs.<br>
<br>
b) Your chanter is being pounded on by several mobs. You target him and cast Stun Command. The AE goes around from the chanter and all the mobs that are pounding on him are frozen for a few moments, giving him time to mez, as well as giving you time to heal. Cast time of SC is very low. <br>
<br>
I would say that Stun Command is great in mid 50s, which is when it was designed to be used. Its usefulness diminishes in high-end game because all the 60+ mobs are unstunnable, and you don't get a lot of chance to use any stuns period.<br>
<br>
